Bye bye2022!
•
2022 was a good year for our family.
•
Starting with the opportunity of a life time to participate in a tv show. It challenged us to the very core and showed us how important each of us are to our family and although not perfect we need each other. We are still a work in progress. Stay tuned for our episode on @survivalists_byutv @byutv 
•
Our oldest son finished high school this year. Unfortunately, he was not able to participate on the tv show with us, we are very proud of him as he enters adulthood.
•
Our daughter worked so hard for try outs for the cheer leading squad and made it. Her hard perseverance paid off. Along with cheerleading she is able to get straight A’s and a clear view of her future - she will do it!
•
The youngest played his first year of football. It was a challenge; however, he stayed focused and finished strong. He is now in basketball and enjoying it. He is still coding and working on building his YouTube channel.
•
Work life is ever changing! I received a new position with my work and making a difference in caregiving. My husbands work is changing a lot; however, is still a blessing.
•
We look forward to 2023 and all the great blessings and the lords hand over all our family for safety and health. 
•
 Happy New Year 2023 IG family! Wishing God brings you love, health, peace, joy, happiness and wealth in 2023 and years to come! Xoxo Ale

It’s finally here! Today is the day for our episode to be aired and we can wait for you to know and learn a little bit more about us. 
•
Before we even arrive to Cabo San Lucas, we saw the Tran family in the airport and we kind of had the feeling without knowing each other that they were possible our rivals. We also meet the Yoffee and Phillips family, all of them with an amazing story and great people with their own journey of love. 
•
As soon as we arrived everything went really fast, we meet the crew and they made us feel safe and we were grateful to have them with us all the time, they are the unseen heroes, our portion of our episode was filmed in one week and they were there for more than a month, running and staying close with the rest of the other families, just amazing!.
•
We were all excited about the show but reality set at the very beginning of the race, we underestimated the physical and emotional demands of survivalists.
•
We carried everything for us to “survive” 4 days in the desert in our bag pack!.We were totally out of our comfort zone with not electronics and truly in the wilderness where we encountered scorpions 🦂, snakes 🐍, coyotes, etc.  We did not take showers and had minimal clothing options. We were sunburned to the point of allergic reaction. We ate dehydrated food seasoned with a lot of sand from the island, our bodies hurt in places that we did not know existed. 
•
In the end the experience accomplished the task to bring our family closer, and all was totally worth it. Our episode with survivalists has ended but our journey continues and we got so much from our time on the show! Please watch us today. You can stream it live on BYUtv, byutv.org or any of this apps (Roku, Apple TV, Amazon Fire stick, iOS, Android). You’ll be able to find the episode on demand after it airs at any point on all the above mentioned platforms. Link in bio!
•
Big thanks to all the @survivalists_byutv film crew, medic team, @byutv for an amazing once in a life time experience!.
•

This year I turned 44 years old, I’m a mom of a 15 year old daughter and 11 year old son both with busy schedules, I work full time from home in front of a computer all day and have really bad sleeping habits and sessional depression. Let’s be honest, I wish I could tell you age does not affect you but it really does. Every year my metabolism gets slower and if I don’t do something for my self I know it will not get better. 

When the opportunity came to try @otfherriman in @shopmvvillage I did not think it twice and on January 16th I started the 8 week challenge. they completed a body composition analysis for me and the numbers did not surprise me because I have been a couch potato for long time! My weight was 154.3 lbs, skeletal muscle mass 51.4 lbs and my percentage body fat was 39%. 

I attended 37 classes over the 8 weeks and I will tell you there were a couple of times where I really just wanted to stay in bed or I was too busy and did not want to put the workout as a priority. As you probably guessed I stayed at home and slept more or I did everything except working out, Surprisingly I can count those times with one hand! During these 37 classes I burned 18,081 calories total and received 559 splat points. On March 12th I had my follow up body composition scan and my weight was 151.9 lbs, skeletal muscle mass 51.6 lbs and my percentage body fat was 38.3 %. 

I know this is not a big change but it is still progress and even though I’m not where I want to be I know I’m on my way. When started this journey I was not looking for a quick fix, I was looking for something that would help me feel better both mentally and physically. I can tell you for sure, every time I go to #orangetheory I feel I’m taking care of my self, my body and my mental health. I feel stronger, accomplished and happy! 

What is next? This journey has not ended with these 8 weeks, I continue working with the relationship I have with food, my sleeping habits, my body, my brain and God! 

Thank you for all of you that send me messages of support while I was doing the challenge and if you want to know more about #orangetheoryfitness and their #8weekchallenge just let me know! Xoxo Ale

Victoria is turning 16th today. Long before she was born I had already named her. It happens that I only have one ovary and I was told by the doctor it would be difficult for me to get pregnant. 

In my mind and a lot of faith, I decided to name her Victoria as she was going to be a total victory for me. Her middle name is (Faith) because of test results and the doctor told me she was going to be a special baby with Down syndrome. 

I don’t know you but I believe in Gods’s miracles and if he was giving me a baby I knew she would be born healthy no matter what her condition. 

I loved my pregnancy even when I had to poke my belly and fingers before and after I ate because of gestational diabetes or the nausea that lasted 7 months. 

I loved how strong she was and kicked my belly to the point that it hurt. I just loved the feel she was alive,cozy and warm in my womb. In fact she was so comfortable that she stayed inside 5 days past her due date and had to be induced. 

I remember arriving to the hospital on a snowy day, all excited because soon she was going to be in my arms! After 13 hrs of labor she was born healthy and strong. As soon as she was in my arms the pain was gone! 

She completed me and change my life forever! Today I celebrate another milestone with her, she is turning 16 and I could not be more happy and proud of her beyond belief. God blessed me with a strong heart, caring, compassionate and loving daughter. 

Happy sweet sixteen my princess. @victoriabetton_ I’ll keep watching you grow and I will always be your biggest fan, I will love you forever and ever no matter what, no matter when, no matter how, no matter the space. Xoxo Mom. #happysweet16 #mybabygirl #theprincessofthehouse #16thbirthday #loveyouforever❤️
